states</a></nav><main class="content">< !--==============00 THESIS==============--><section class="section" id="thesis"><div class="kicker">Corpass · B2B Procurement &amp;
Asset Platform</div><h1>A procurement platform that reads like a ledger,
not a brochure.</h1><p class="lead">Corpass moves real corporate money between companies. The design language is built for that weight: precise,
auditable,
and calm — closer to a well-kept financial ledger than a consumer marketplace.</p><h3>The single idea everything hangs on</h3><p>Most B2B SaaS looks the same because it decorates first and decides later. Corpass decides first. The product is about <strong>quantities,
prices,
identifiers,
and the state of a transaction over time</strong>— so those are the things we typeset with the most care.</p><div class="callout"><p><b>The Ledger.</b>Every monetary value,
quantity,
order ID,
GSTIN,
pincode,
and stock count is rendered in a monospaced face (IBM Plex Mono),
right-aligned when numeric,
and separated by hairline rules. Money lines up. Numbers tabulate. The eye can scan a column the way an accountant does. This one decision is the through-line from the landing hero to the stock table — it is what makes Corpass recognizably itself.</p></div><h3>What we are deliberately <em>not</em>building</h3><ul class="clean"><li><strong>Not the SaaS-indigo template.</strong>No violet gradient hero,
no rounded-everything,
no purple primary. Our identity color is evergreen — it reads as money,
stability,
and growth,
and it is uncommon enough to own.</li><li><strong>Not a sea of identical cards.</strong>Dashboards use asymmetric bento tiles with a clear focal point and dense,
elegant tables — the discipline of SAP Fiori with the finish of Stripe — never a uniform 4×4 grid of equal boxes.</li><li><strong>Not lists for the sake of lists.</strong>Where data is relational and scannable (orders, stock, catalog) we use a real ledger table. Lists are reserved for genuinely linear content (a conversation, an activity feed).</li></ul><div class="bento" style="grid-template-columns:1.4fr 1fr 1fr"><div class="card"><h4>Precision over polish</h4><p>If a number is wrong by a rupee,
the design has failed. Alignment,
tabular figures,
and clear state come before flourish.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Density done well</h4><p>Procurement teams scan a lot at once. We earn density with hierarchy,
rhythm,
and rules — not by cramming.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Two audiences,
one grammar</h4><p>Buyer and seller share the same components and tokens;
only the verbs and accents change. One product,
two doors.</p></div></div></section>< !--==============01 VOICE==============--><section class="section" id="voice"><div class="kicker">01 — Brand &amp;
Voice</div><h2>Plain,
exact,
and quietly confident.</h2><p>Corpass talks the way a good procurement manager does: it never oversells,
it is specific about money and timelines,
and it tells you exactly what a button will do before you press it.</p><div class="two"><div><h4>Tone principles</h4><ul class="clean"><li><strong>Name actions by their consequence.</strong>"Place order",
"Request quote",
"Mark shipped" — not "Submit" or "Confirm" .</li><li><strong>One verb,
end to end.</strong>The button that says "Place order" produces a toast that says "Order placed" . The vocabulary never drifts.</li><li><strong>Sentence case everywhere.</strong>Titles,
buttons,
labels. Title Case reads as marketing;
